title: Streamlit Deployment on Health Universe
body:
Hi All,

Great project! Have you considered Streamlit as a UI and possible deployment on Health Universe? Is there anyone on the team that would consider working on this? I can help. Deploying the application makes it runnable from the browser and allows far greater distribution and ease of use, to enable more citations and greater impact. Does that make sense?

Dan Caron
Health Universe

title: Torch incompatibility with Numpy 2
body:

Some module may need to rebuild instead e.g. with 'pybind11>=2.12'.

If you are a user of the module, the easiest solution will be to

title: Pre-training Code
body: Thank you for the impressive work! I was wondering if it would be possible for you to release the pre-training code? It would be extremely helpful for understanding the underlying mechanisms combined with the paper.

title: Pre-trained Model Weights
body:
I hope this message finds you well. I have been exploring your excellent work on Orthrus from your GitHub repository and I wanted to express my appreciation for making it available. However, I couldn’t find the pre-trained model weights in the repository. Could you kindly let me know if they are available, and if so, where I could access them?
Thank you for your time, and I look forward to hearing from you.

title: Shape Mismatch Error in 4track Model (epoch=18-step=20000.ckpt)
body:
I encountered a RuntimeError while using the 4-track model (orthrus_base_4_track) example. Specifically, when my input torch_one_hot has a shape of (1, 4, 495), I get the following error:

`RuntimeError: mat1 and mat2 shapes cannot be multiplied (495x4 and 6x256)`
Upon inspecting the model, I noticed that the embedding layer is defined as:

`(embedding): Linear(in_features=6, out_features=256, bias=True)`
Since in_features is set to 6, the error occurs when torch_one_hot has 4 features. However, when I modify the input to have a shape of (1, 6, 495), the code runs successfully and produces an output of `torch.Size([1, 256])`.

Question:
Is there a version of the model that works with a 4-track input, or is it necessary to use zero padding to convert the input to 6 features?
Thanks

title: Questions about pre-training data
body: Hi, I notice that in the example, there exists T in mRNA information. Does it mean you utilize cDNA information of mRNA for training? It seems that other RNA foundation model utilizes ACGU as tokens: https://github.com/ml4bio/RNA-FM. Are there any advantages for not including U? If yes, can Orthrus be used to generate DNA embeddings? Thanks a lot.
